@ppadma Here is a good summary of how an average of normally distributed data relates to the data itself https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-normal-distribution.html .

If you are computing an average of normally distributed data 50% of the data will be less than the average and 50% will be greater than the average. Therefore if we are using averages to compute row counts for output batches, 50% of the output batches will be less than the target size and 50% will be larger. The degree to which output batch sizes deviate from the average is dictated by the standard deviation.

Such situations are unavoidable with a statistics based approach, which is fine. But we should handle the degenerate case where output batches exceed the target batch size.

@ilooner that is generalizing way too much. What we are trying to accomplish here is use real data to figure out the memory needed. Before, we would use standard size of 50 for varchar, which can differ from average actual varchar column size (could be by a big factor).  Typically, within a column, data will be around the same size and that could differ from standard size we are using by a big factor. What we are trying to optimize here is for accounting for that factor. In my opinion, distribution you are referring to is not applicable here. Also, assuming that data will be more or less evenly distributed across partitions, again, I believe stating that 50% of the batches will be more than average and 50% less than average is also wrong. 

Since we are calculating batch size upfront, emitting partial batches and keeping track of all that is unnecessary complication that can be avoided. I don't think it will provide much benefit. 

Allowing the HashAgg operator to decrease the output batch size configured by the user - Yes, that we have to do. In fact, that is the problem I am having with hash join right now which is causing hash join to spill.

@vvysotskyi This is actually desired behavior since the `VectorUtil.showVectorAccessibleContent` method now uses a logger to print its messages. By default loggers are configure to output to lilith for unit tests, so it will not show up on the console. If you want the log messages to be printed to stdout you need to explicitly enable them with the log fixture:

```
try(LogFixture logFixture = new LogFixture.LogFixtureBuilder()
      .logger("org.apache.drill", Level.OFF) // This is to disable the rest of Drill's debug messages which clog of the screen
      .logger(VectorUtil.class, Level.INFO) // Show results
      .toConsole() // This redirects output to stdout
      .build()) {
  // printResult here
}
```

Then after you are done debugging the test you can remove the log fixture to avoid printing extra messages on travis and jenkins.

